<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="71" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="71">
<taxonomicName LSID="6597B833-CB6A-5AB5-815B-ACDC70EFFA4B" authority="Zhang, 1994, species inquirenda" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Bombus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Bombus anacolus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anacolus">&quot; Bombus &quot; anacolus Zhang, 1994, species inquirenda</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="71" type="holotype">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="71">Holotype.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="71">
Female. Plate XXXIII-2, figs 165, 166, 167 in 
<bibRefCitation author="Zhang, JF" journalOrPublisher="Science Press, Beijing" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" refId="B147" refString="Zhang, JF, Sun, B, Zhang, XY, 1994. Miocene Insects and Spiders from Shanwang, Shandong. Science Press, Beijing" title="Miocene Insects and Spiders from Shanwang, Shandong." year="1994">Zhang et al. (1994)</bibRefCitation>
. We were not able study the holotype (see comment under 
<taxonomicName genus="B." lsidName="B. luianus" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" rank="species" species="luianus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">B. luianus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, vide supra).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="71" type="type strata and locality">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="71">Type strata and locality.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="71">Middle Miocence (i.e., 17.0-15.2 Ma), deposit of the Shanwang Formation, large lacustrine and lithified deposit, with diatomaceous and tuffaceous mudstone. Located in Linqu County, Shanwang Province, China.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="71" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="71">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="71">
Taken from 
<bibRefCitation author="Zhang, JF" journalOrPublisher="Science Press, Beijing" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" refId="B147" refString="Zhang, JF, Sun, B, Zhang, XY, 1994. Miocene Insects and Spiders from Shanwang, Shandong. Science Press, Beijing" title="Miocene Insects and Spiders from Shanwang, Shandong." year="1994">Zhang et al. (1994)</bibRefCitation>
: Forewing blackish brown, opaque; forewing and hind wing papillate distally; forewing length approximately 15.0 mm, maximum width approximately 6.00 mm as preserved; basal vein relatively straight and basad cu-a; cu-a almost straight; marginal cell length almost 5.0 mm, width 1.1 mm; 1st abscissa of Rs almost straight; 2nd abscissa of Rs slightly curved near midpoint; r-rs straight; Rs+M straight and longer than r-rs; 3Rs straight and smaller than r-rs; 4Rs straight and approximately as long as Rs+M; three submarginal cells, second smallest; 1rs-m straight; 2rs-m curved apically in its posterior half; 1m-cu relatively straight, reaching M near midpoint between 2nd abscissa of Rs and 1rs-m; 2m-cu curved apically, reaching M basad to 2rs-m; total body length approximately 13.0 mm as preserved (large part of metasoma missing). See 
<bibRefCitation author="Zhang, JF" journalOrPublisher="Science Press, Beijing" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" refId="B147" refString="Zhang, JF, Sun, B, Zhang, XY, 1994. Miocene Insects and Spiders from Shanwang, Shandong. Science Press, Beijing" title="Miocene Insects and Spiders from Shanwang, Shandong." year="1994">Zhang et al. (1994)</bibRefCitation>
for original description.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="71" type="comments">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="71">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="71">
The specimen was described as 
<taxonomicName genus="B." lsidName="B. anacolus" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" rank="species" species="anacolus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">B. anacolus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Zhang, JF" journalOrPublisher="Science Press, Beijing" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" refId="B147" refString="Zhang, JF, Sun, B, Zhang, XY, 1994. Miocene Insects and Spiders from Shanwang, Shandong. Science Press, Beijing" title="Miocene Insects and Spiders from Shanwang, Shandong." year="1994">Zhang et al. (1994)</bibRefCitation>
, and considered to be close to 
<taxonomicName genus="B." lsidName="B. luianus" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" rank="species" species="luianus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">B. luianus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, a species collected from the same deposit. Based on geometric morphometric analyses this species is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Skorikov, 1914" authorityName="Skorikov" authorityYear="1914" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Mendacibombus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Mendacibombus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">Mendacibombus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and it could be a relative of this subgenus. This hypothesis is supported by the fact that 
<taxonomicName authority="Skorikov, 1914" authorityName="Skorikov" authorityYear="1914" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Mendacibombus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Mendacibombus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">Mendacibombus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is estimated to have originated around the Eocene-Oligocene boundary (i.e., 34 Ma) in the Old World (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/10635150801898912" author="Hines, HM" journalOrPublisher="Systematic Biology" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" pagination="58 - 75" refId="B55" refString="Hines, HM, 2008. Historical biogeography, divergence times, and diversification patterns of bumblebees (Hymenoptera: Apidae: Bombus). Systematic Biology 57: 58 - 75" title="Historical biogeography, divergence times, and diversification patterns of bumblebees (Hymenoptera: Apidae: Bombus)." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/10635150801898912" volume="57" year="2008">Hines 2008</bibRefCitation>
), while the fossil was discovered in the Middle Lower Miocene (i.e., 17.0-15.2 Ma) deposit of Shandong in China (
<bibRefCitation author="Zhang, JF" journalOrPublisher="Acta Zootaxonomica Sinica" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" pagination="83 - 91" refId="B146" refString="Zhang, JF, 1990. New fossil species of Apoidea (Insecta: Hymenoptera). Acta Zootaxonomica Sinica 15: 83 - 91" title="New fossil species of Apoidea (Insecta: Hymenoptera)." volume="15" year="1990">Zhang 1990</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Zhang, JF" journalOrPublisher="Science Press, Beijing" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" refId="B147" refString="Zhang, JF, Sun, B, Zhang, XY, 1994. Miocene Insects and Spiders from Shanwang, Shandong. Science Press, Beijing" title="Miocene Insects and Spiders from Shanwang, Shandong." year="1994">Zhang et al. 1994</bibRefCitation>
). Moreover, the crown age of extant members of 
<taxonomicName authority="Skorikov, 1914" authorityName="Skorikov" authorityYear="1914" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Mendacibombus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Mendacibombus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">Mendacibombus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
apparently diversified during the Late Miocene (i.e., 8 Ma). As observed for 
<taxonomicName genus="B." lsidName="B. luianus" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" rank="species" species="luianus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">B. luianus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="B." lsidName="B. dilectus" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" rank="species" species="dilectus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">B. dilectus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, results based on geometric morphometric analyses for this species could be wrong since it was based on 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Zhang’s">Zhang's</normalizedToken>
drawings. Given this, we consider the fossil as species inquirenda.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
